commentBody:
@Zeldie
No can do on the kale substitute. 
Kale is extremely overrated, and wholly undeserving of its current ubiquity.

Concerned about the prospect of too much lemon, I used the zest of 1 medium lemon (but no juice). And instead of EVOO, used lemon-infused OO both in the sauce and to garnish-- fantastic. Garnished w/ Parm & black pepper, too.

@Alison: Thx! When using a blender, in order for the ingredients to "catch" in the blade, I prefer to add the liquid (pasta water) first, then the dry ingredients. 

@AEC and Judy, I did make this using organic 2% cottage cheese--the flavor and richness were quite good.

@Debbie
Have never seen pitted Medjool dates sold.. only the firmer Deglet ones. It’s so easy to remove the pit because they are softer..
Best dates(and date varieties) are at Kalustyan’s 123 Lexington Ave NYC(foodsofnations.com)

@Kelsey 
Rancho Gordo has some thoughts on this. I think they are cooked so long in this dish you probably don’t need to soak them. 

<a href="https://www.ranchogordo.com/blogs/blog/the-eternal-question-bean-soaking-or-not" target="_blank">https://www.ranchogordo.com/blogs/blog/the-eternal-question-bean-soaking-or-not</a>

@LeAnne Hale

Or celery. 

However, for those who are hesitating about the fennel, I suggest you give it a try, just once. When braised, fennel really mellows out and does not taste strongly of licorice
